## Review of `app.js`

The current code is a minimal Express app. It works fine for a stub, but has several gaps in security hardening and resilience.

---

### 🔴 Critical / Security Issues

#### 1. No Security Headers
The app sends no security-related HTTP headers, leaving it vulnerable to common web attacks (clickjacking, MIME sniffing, etc.). Use [`helmet`](https://helmetjs.github.io/):

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet());
```

#### 2. No Rate Limiting
All endpoints are wide open to brute-force or DoS. Add [`express-rate-limit`](https://github.com/express-rate-limit/express-rate-limit):

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, max: 100 })); // 100 req/15min
```

#### 3. No CORS Policy
Without explicit CORS configuration, cross-origin behavior is uncontrolled in some environments. Use the [`cors`](https://github.com/expressjs/cors) package with an allowlist:

```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({ origin: process.env.ALLOWED_ORIGIN || 'https://yourdomain.com' }));
```

---

### 🟠 Error Handling Issues

#### 4. No Global Error Handler
Express errors (thrown synchronously or passed via `next(err)`) go unhandled. Add a 4-argument error handler **after all routes**:

```js
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err.stack);
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({
    error: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production' ? 'Internal Server Error' : err.message
  });
});
```
> **Note:** In production, never expose raw error messages or stack traces to clients — they leak implementation details.

#### 5. No 404 Handler
Unmatched routes silently fall through. Add a catch-all:

```js
app.use((req, res) => {
  res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not Found' });
});
```

#### 6. No Unhandled Rejection / Exception Handling
If async code or third-party code throws, the process can crash silently or in undefined ways:

```js
process.on('uncaughtException', (err) => {
  console.error('Uncaught Exception:', err);
  process.exit(1); // fail fast and let the process manager restart
});

process.on('unhandledRejection', (reason) => {
  console.error('Unhandled Rejection:', reason);
  process.exit(1);
});
```

---

### 🟡 Input Validation & Hardening

#### 7. Hardcoded Port
The port should come from an environment variable to support different environments:

```js
const PORT = parseInt(process.env.PORT, 10) || 3000;
app.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`));
```

#### 8. No Body Parser / Size Limit
If `POST`/`PUT` routes are ever added, the lack of a body size limit is a DoS vector. Add this proactively:

```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true, limit: '10kb' }));
```

#### 9. No Request Logging
Without structured request logging, debugging and detecting attacks (repeated errors, scanning patterns) is hard. Use [`morgan`](https://github.com/expressjs/morgan):

```js
const morgan = require('morgan');
app.use(morgan('combined')); // or 'dev' for local development
```

---

### ✅ Suggested Hardened `app.js`

```js
const express = require('express');
const helmet = require('helmet');
const cors = require('cors');
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
const morgan = require('morgan');

const app = express();
const PORT = parseInt(process.env.PORT, 10) || 3000;

// Security middleware
app.use(helmet());
app.use(cors({ origin: process.env.ALLOWED_ORIGIN || false }));
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, max: 100 }));

// Request parsing with size limits
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true, limit: '10kb' }));

// Logging
app.use(morgan(process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production' ? 'combined' : 'dev'));

// Routes
app.get('/health', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: 'ok', timestamp: new Date().toISOString() });
});

app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json([
    { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
    { id: 2, name: 'Bob', email: 'bob@example.com' },
  ]);
});

// 404 handler
app.use((req, res) => {
  res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not Found' });
});

// Global error handler
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err.stack);
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({
    error: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production' ? 'Internal Server Error' : err.message,
  });
});

// Process-level error handling
process.on('uncaughtException', (err) => {
  console.error('Uncaught Exception:', err);
  process.exit(1);
});
process.on('unhandledRejection', (reason) => {
  console.error('Unhandled Rejection:', reason);
  process.exit(1);
});

app.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`));

module.exports = app;
```

---

### Summary of Changes

| Issue | Severity | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| No security headers | 🔴 High | Add `helmet` |
| No rate limiting | 🔴 High | Add `express-rate-limit` |
| No CORS policy | 🔴 High | Add `cors` with origin allowlist |
| No global error handler | 🟠 Medium | Add 4-arg error middleware |
| No 404 handler | 🟠 Medium | Add catch-all route |
| No crash protection | 🟠 Medium | Handle `uncaughtException` / `unhandledRejection` |
| Hardcoded port | 🟡 Low | Use `process.env.PORT` |
| No body size limit | 🟡 Low | Set `limit` on body parsers |
| No request logging | 🟡 Low | Add `morgan` |

